I think I get, what you're talking about, guys. So, currently DRF-ME's `FileField` returns `grid_id` instead of a hyperlink to the file content (that's what DRF's FileField does and probably what we should).

@iKeepWalking I'm not sure that streaming a base64-encoded file back is a good solution. Currently, I'm reading about how to overcome this with Mongoengine, as we can't rely upon django's media mechanism for this.

This is not very nice, and hopefully they fix this issue, but for those who want a workaround until then, you can edit `request.py` in this package, changing the last few lines instead to be:

```
    # if redirects are disabled, don't raise for 301 / 302
    if result.status_code in (301, 302):
        if allow_redirects:
            result.raise_for_status()
    elif result.status_code in (401, ):
        if result.headers['Status'] == "201 Created":
            result = requests.get("{}?oauth_token={}".format(
                                  result.headers['Location'], data['oauth_token']))
    else:
        result.raise_for_status()
    return result
```

This will basically check for the 401 + 201 Created case, then request the Location header using the oauth_token, and then return that as the response.

@gglanzani Sorry for the delay.  Trying to understand your situation. So you are running your own, custom Erlang `yearfun` on your nodes.  You are getting the desired results in **curl**, but are only getting a partial result with the Python HTTP interface, right? And PBC seems to raise an exception in this case, right?

I'm looking at our current test cases and all of them seem to return a list values, not more complicated types like proplists.  I could see that **curl** is simply blurping back whatever Erlang returns, but the Python client has to serialize and deserialize.  As you can see from the PBC results, it's trying to convert it into a Python dict(), which is the source of the exception.  I'm interested that the HTTP sort of works. I'm guessing it is unpacking part of the JSON we get back from Riak and throwing the rest on the floor.

So my guess at the moment is the Python client is only supporting returning a list of values.  We could look at lists of dicts() as an enhancement.

@randy3k, the `.ropeproject` folder currently cannot be disable by user settings because the `python-language-server` receives the settings from the language client, after loading the server plugins: https://github.com/palantir/python-language-server/pull/253#discussion_r164610715

https://github.com/palantir/python-language-server/blob/b0dc780e2e177cd1149e685e235419e0ec67841b/pyls/workspace.py#L84-L89

This way we cannot configure the plugins load options. But you can change directly your client code as the one above to pass by default `ropefolder=None`. This way the `ropeproject` folder is never created.

