@dklimkin 
I'd argue that the library is working as intended when it fails to parse XML containing characters that are out of [range](https://www.w3.org/TR/xml/#charsets) for the specification. I don't think we should make any exceptions, as that would just mask the underlying issue of fields successfully being set to values containing invalid characters.

I'm pretty confident this is not a client-library specific issue, as it sounds like there is validation missing somewhere that allowed this control character to be set for the customer name. Of course, determining where that customer name was set would help us resolve the issue. :-)

@aisir 
To fix this particular issue for you, the control character will need to be removed from any affected customer names. That's not something I can do on the issue tracker for this library, but the [AdWords API Support Forum](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/adwords-api) should be able to help with this.

@roll The code looks good, it just needs a few tweaks to be more consistent with the overall style of this package. For instance, instead of having `pull_datapackage` and `push_datapackage`, we'd have `DataPackage.pull()` as a class method which returns a `DataPackage` instance, and `datapackage.push()` as an instance method.

To be honest, I prefer `DataPackage.from_storage()` and `datapackage.to_storage()`, but that might be because "push" is a tricky word for me. It sounds the same as the Portuguese word "puxe", which means "pull". It takes me a second to translate, which makes pulling doors with "push" signs in them :sweat_smile:

Push/pull are very common for devs, though, so I'm happy to keep it.

