For future reference, I've done this code to convert global_id on mutations, it's not complete and I'll create a PR as soon I cover all scenarios and finish my project.

```python
class DjangoModelFormRelayMutation(DjangoModelFormMutation):
    class Meta:
        abstract = True

    @classmethod
    def mutate_and_get_payload(cls, root, info, **input):
        model = cls._meta.form_class._meta.model

        for field, value in input.items():
            if not hasattr(model, field):
                continue

            model_field = model._meta.get_field(field)
            #TODO: Convert to singledispatch
            if isinstance(model_field, (AutoField, ForeignKey)):
                _, input[field] = from_global_id(value)

    return super().mutate_and_get_payload(root, info, **input)
```

Hope it helps you @zbyte64 in the mean time.

@michaelsembwever FWIW, it's not superfluous -- `JoinTrace(Span)` is not present in https://github.com/opentracing/opentracing-go/pull/40, for example.

Regardless, there is still a question about whether this functionality belongs on `Span` or `Tracer`... the former reduces the number of interfaces a typical user has to interact with and also eliminates the need for both a `Span` and `Tracer` instance just to create a child (which should be the *common* case of `Span` creation, of course, or traces are not deep/useful). The latter puts the two basic cases of Span creation next to one and other... or, in python, they can be the same method (which is nice).

Anyway, I think there are some false dichotomies about plumbing vs porcelain; I would rather think from first principles about how OpenTracing will be used and aim for fluidity.

